      "hypothesis": "In BULL_STRESSED, short-horizon downside dislocations within an intact uptrend are systematically over-extended and revert toward the short-term mean within roughly two weeks. The tradeable side is LONG: fade 2-sigma lower-band excursions on a 10-bar window (orthogonal to the regime's 20-bar vol and 63-bar trend definitions). Reversion quality should be strongest when macro stress is easing rather than building - falling 5-day VIX change, lower real-yield z-score, and softer breakeven-inflation impulses mark liquidity returning, so the meta-learner conditioned on these exogenous drivers should separate genuine dip-reversion from continuation breaks.",
      "causal_story": "The dossier shows the mean-reversion primary is the only one with above-median hit rate in this regime while trend/momentum primaries sit at their worst - high realized vol inside a bull tape means dips are noise-driven, not information-driven. Mechanically, stressed pullbacks force short-horizon de-risking (vol-target and stop-loss selling) against holders whose longer-horizon view is unchanged; once forced flow exhausts, price snaps back to the mean. The exogenous discriminators are LOWER here (vix_chg_5 0.479, real_yield_5y_z252d 0.382, breakeven_5y_chg5 0.437): stress is elevated in level but not accelerating, the classic window where liquidity providers re-enter and fade extensions. Volume is LOWER (0.468), consistent with dips on thin participation rather than distribution.",
      "feature_overrides": {
        "add": [
          "volume",
          "vix_chg_5",
          "real_yield_5y_z252d",
          "breakeven_5y_chg5",
